# Test-Driven Development

All feature implementation MUST follow this TDD cycle. Do not skip steps or proceed without explicit user approval at review gates.

## Prerequisites

A technical PRD must exist for the feature being implemented (in `docs/technical_prds/` or provided by the user). If no PRD is available, STOP and ask the user to provide one before proceeding.

## Cycle

### Step 1: Write tests

Write tests for the feature described in the PRD. Cover the expected behavior, edge cases, and error conditions outlined in the requirements. Do not write any implementation code yet.

### Step 2: Run tests (expect failures)

Run the test suite. All new tests should FAIL at this point since no implementation exists. If any new test passes, it is either testing existing behavior or is incorrectly written — flag this to the user.

### Step 3: Review gate (user approval required)

STOP and present the tests to the user for review. Do not proceed to implementation until the user explicitly approves the tests. If the user requests changes, revise and re-run before continuing.

### Step 4: Implement the feature

Write the implementation code to make the failing tests pass. Follow the architecture and conventions defined in the project rules and PRD.

### Step 5: Run tests (expect passes)

Run the full test suite. If all tests pass, proceed to Step 6. If any tests fail, debug and fix until green — do not move forward with failing tests.

### Step 6: Review gate (user approval required)

STOP and present both the tests and implementation to the user for final review. Do not proceed to the next phase until the user explicitly approves.

### Step 7: Next phase

Once approved, move to the next implementation phase defined in the PRD and repeat from Step 1.
